%N A389235 Number of repeating Harshad algorithm steps until a non-Harshad number or a power of 10 is reached.
%C A389235 a(n) is the number of Harshad algorithm steps that can be done starting with n and always reaching another Harshad number (See also A114440). Stopping points are non-Harshad numbers or Harshad numbers that are a powers of 10 (See example).
%H A389235 Karl-Heinz Hofmann, <a href="/A389235/b389235.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A389235 Brady Haran and Tony Padilla, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dgwevhEykWQ">The Joy of Harshad Numbers</a>, YouTube video, 2025.
%H A389235 Eric Weisstein, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HarshadNumber.html">Harshad Numbers</a>.
%H A389235 Wikipedia, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harshad_number">Harshad number</a>.
%e A389235 a(20) = 1 because digit sum of 20 is 2 and 20/2 = 10.
%e A389235 10 is in fact a Harshad number too, but a Harshad number with an infinite cycle.
%e A389235 So we have to stop here. This happens for all powers of 10.
%e A389235 So a(1), a(10), a(100) ... are always 0.
%t A389235 a[n_] := -1 + Length[NestWhileList[# / DigitSum[#] &, n, DigitSum[#] > 1 && Divisible[#, DigitSum[#]] &]]; Array[a, 100] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 27 2025 *)
%o A389235 (Python)
%o A389235 def A389235(n):
%o A389235     c = 0
%o A389235     while not n % (digsum:=sum([int(d) for d in str(n)])) and digsum != 1: n, c = n // digsum, c + 1
%o A389235     return c
%o A389235 print([A389235(n) for n in range(1, 100)])
%o A389235 (PARI) a(n) = {my(k=0,r=n,s); while((s=sumdigits(r)) != 1 && r%s==0, r/=s; k++); k} \\ _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 26 2025
